It does not, moreover, require a lengthy examination to see that the paschal Ordo does not possess the Roman characteristica of the Ordo of the Mass. In taking up the latter, we leel ourselves transported to Rome, into the midst

oi the Roman clergy, to the city with its seven regions, and its special days of service lor each region. The

officiating minister is the Pope himself, dcccco apostolicas, who appears surrounded by the great dignitaries of his court-the primiciarius, the scmradiccrics, the miccius, the oomcwictm and others. He starts from his Palaoe oi the Lateran and proceeds on horseback in procession to one or other oi the Roman basilicas. Itis clearly impossible to refer these details to any other locality. In the paschal Ordo, on the contrary, there are no indicatione of any particular town, while it is an ordinary dignitany-a bishop -who officiatos, and sometimes even merely an inferior ecclesiastic. The use is indeed Roman, but Roman as observed elsewhere than in Rome, and combining with incusans unknown to the papal court.

Itis therefore impossible to attach the same weight to the paschal Ordo as to the rest. It contains, doubtless, many Roman details, but details which in every case require to be confirmed by more trustworthy documenta.
